"},"en":{"about 1480–about 1505":"about 1480–about 1505","1480–1505":"1480–1505","1480–1509":"1480–1509","1430–1509":"1430–1509","1475–1547":"1475–1547","1494–1525":"1494–1525","1498–Female":"1498–Deceased","1501–1554":"1501–1554","1502–1510":"1502–1510","1450–Male":"1450–Deceased","1455–Female":"1455–Deceased","about 1480":"about 1480","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1502":"1502","1501":"1501","about 1505":"about 1505","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1554":"1554","1498":"1498","1475":"1475","about 1502":"about 1502","1430":"1430","Abt. 1498":"about 1498","before 1494":"before 1494","1509":"1509","1505":"1505","Andover, Hampshire, England":"Andover, Hampshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Marton, Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hardon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Pakistan): variant of   Harun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Harun","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Bangladesh): from the personal name <i>Hārūn</i>, the Arabic form of the Biblical   Aaron  , and mentioned thus in the Koran, Sura 19:53. Compare   Haroon   and   Haroun  .","History: The name <i>Hārūn</i> was borne by the fifth Abbasid caliph Hārūn al-Rashīd (ruled 786–809)."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla"